   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

   "source": [
    "For a more complex system, the compositional geometric model allows for specification of arbitrary shapes. This can be scaled up arbitrarily; up to Imagenet pictures -- you simply need to provide numpy arrays. For this purpose, I will implement a more elaborate hierarchical transitional system -- but the underlying pilgrimm class allows for such modifications already (see below)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "cgm = patches.datasets.compositional_geometric_model(\n",
    "    width=10,\n",
    "    shapes=[[patches.datasets.pilgrimm.horizontal(2),\n",
    "             patches.datasets.pilgrimm.vertical(2)],\n",
    "            [patches.datasets.pilgrimm.diagonal(2),\n",
    "             patches.datasets.pilgrimm.antidiagonal(2)]],\n",
    "    change_probs=[0.05, 0.5],\n",
    "    samples=100\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },

   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## On occlusion"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The data will be complicated by certain frames in which the information may only partially or not at all be available. This can be addressed by an autoregressive model, and the simplest use case is the occluded binary model below:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "obm = patches.datasets.occluded_binary_model(\n",
    "    width=10,\n",
    "    change_probs=[0.05, 0.5],\n",
    "    occlusion_range=0.01,\n",
    "    occlusion_probs=0.1,\n",
    "    samples=100\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },

   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Object impermanence"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Another dataset may contrast object permanence and impermanence. The 'magic' argument may also be applied to the occluding arguments above."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 18,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "sgm = patches.datasets.sequential_geometric_model(\n",
    "    width=10,\n",
    "    shapes=[\n",
    "        patches.datasets.pilgrimm.vertical(n)\\\n",
    "        for n in range(2, 11)\n",
    "    ],\n",
    "    occlusion_range=0.01,\n",
    "    occlusion_probs=[0.1],\n",
    "    samples=100,\n",
    "    magic=True\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
